defaultrime, regional Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners have agreed to a new single command model which incorporates regional Counter Terrorism (CT) and Serious and Organised Crime (SOC) assets. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn 2010 Chief Constables and representatives of the 
defaultp
defaultolice 
defaulta
defaultuthorities signed Section 23 agreements for the South East Regional Organised Crime Unit (SEROCU), South East Covert Operations (SECOU), South East Technical Surveillance (SETSU) and the South East Protected Person Scheme (SEPPS). These regional units were formed from existing Force capability and based upon a ‘Lead Force’ model with Sussex leading SEROCU, Thames Valley SETSU, Hampshire SEPPS and Surrey SECOU.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn
default November 2012 three options were 
defaultconsidered by the Chief Constables across the South East region 
defaultfor the future approach to tackling SOC and CT in the region. The option to develop a single command model incorporating regional CT and SOC assets supported by a common infrastructure was 
defaultsubsequently 
defaultagreed by the Chief Constables and PCCs. 
defaultThis initiative is intended to complement the work of the National Crime Agency.
default&#xa0;
defaultFollowing this decision a programme of work started with a two phased approach. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe first phase of work is now complete which saw the alignment of the SEROCU, SECOU, SETSU and SEPPS under a single command structure.
default&#xa0;
defaultPhase Two
default is now underway with detailed planning taking place to develop and implement the future command model and alignment to the South East Counter Terrorism Unit. Subject to consultation, the HR model for the realigned regional SOC units will be a Thames Valley Police host force model, with a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) between regional Chief Constables. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition to this the Home Office ha
defaults
default given regional organised crime units a grant to fund the development of additional capabilities in serious organised crime. 
defaultAccordingly, the
default regional Chief Constables and
default Police and Crime Commissioners considered proposals 
defaultto address current capability gaps in confidential unit, prison intelligence, cyber crime and fraud
default and approved the relevant business cases
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultRecruitment for the heads of these new regional units has begun and they will be responsible for building and recruiting their team. They will be employed by the host force (Thames Valley Police) and will sit within the current regional organised crime unit structure.
default&#xa0;
defaultAn 
defaultAssistant Chief Constable has been appointed to lead the new regional CT and SOC command, working for and accountable to the whole region and all five Chief Constables, tak
defaulti
defaultn
defaultg
default up the role with effect from 1
defaultst
default October 2013.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe timescales for the completion for this 
defaultsecond 
defaultphase is April 2014, which includes the first implementation phase for the additional capabilities.
