defaultCollaboration defaultRisks default&#xa0;defaultThe following risks have been identified in relation to the regional delivery of serious organised crime and counter terrorism:
default&#xa0;
default1. 
default              
defaultLoss of skills - there is a risk that key skills will be lost as staff 
defaultmay 
defaultseek employment elsewhere.  This will impact on the ability of units to maintain business as usual.
default&#xa0;
default2. 
default              
defaultStaff morale - there is a risk that morale will decline due to 
default‘
defaultchange fatigue
default’
default,
default which 
defaultmay
default impact on performance.
default&#xa0;
default3. 
default              
defaultInadequate project resourcing - there is a risk that inadequate project resourcing will undermine project delivery and cause delays.
default&#xa0;
default4. 
default              
defaultInternal Change Programmes - conflict of priorities with individual internal 
defaultforce 
defaultchange programmes
default,
default e.g. estates strategies.
default&#xa0;
default5. 
default              
defaultPerceived risk to transparency of tasking - CT assets are nationally owned and co-ordinated and regionally based
default,
default whereas SOC assets are locally owned and regionally based.
default&#xa0;
default6. 
default              
defaultPerceived risk to command/ownership - a host f
defaultorce model is being 
defaultadopt
defaulted;
default the perception could be that the host force would provide the sole command rather than the reality of it being a regional command of regional assets.
default&#xa0;
defaultRisk mitigation action plans have been developed and implemented to address and minimise these risks.
